  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":322,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very relaxed, let your body ease into the effort. No pressure to hit pace in the first few minutes.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable aerobic rhythm. Conversational pace — you should be able to speak in full sentences without gasping.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Gradually ease off. Finish feeling like you could have kept going.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed beyond the easy first 5 minutes. A few dynamic leg swings or ankle circles are welcome if your Achilles feels tight.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 2–3 minutes after finishing. Light calf stretching is a good habit given your Achilles history — keep it gentle, not aggressive.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Monday's easy run is the foundation of your aerobic week. At VDOT 46.7, your easy range is 5:22–5:56/km — aim for the middle to slower end today since it follows a rest day and sets the tone for the week. The goal is blood flow and aerobic stimulus without accumulating fatigue. Your recent training shows you've been consistent and disciplined with easy paces, which is exactly what protects fitness during a maintenance phase.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2Max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":50,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":251,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog. Include 4–6 strides of 20 seconds at interval effort in the final 2 minutes to prime your neuromuscular system before the hard work begins.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":25,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":251,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 × 1 km at 4:11/km (interval pace). This is a controlled hard effort — not a sprint, but genuinely demanding. Focus on smooth, relaxed form even when it gets uncomfortable.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"400m jog recovery between each interval. Keep moving — don't stop. Recovery jogs should feel easy but not so slow that you stiffen up.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"1.6 km easy jog cooldown. Bring your heart rate down gradually.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"2 km easy jog followed by dynamic drills: leg swings, high knees, butt kicks. Finish with 4–6 × 20-second strides at interval effort to prime the legs.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"1.6 km easy jog, then 5 minutes of walking. Gentle calf and Achilles stretching — hold each stretch for 20–30 seconds without bouncing.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This session mirrors what you've been doing successfully — 5 × 1 km at 4:11/km with 400m jog recoveries. In a maintenance phase, the goal of interval work is to preserve your VO2max ceiling, not push it higher. That means hitting the prescribed pace (4:11/km) without going faster. The physiological stimulus you need comes from time near VO2max, and overshooting the pace just adds unnecessary stress. Your recent interval session on March 15 was executed well — same structure, same intent this week.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Recovery\",\"title\":\"Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":356,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Pure recovery pace — 5:56/km or slower is completely fine. This run exists to flush the legs from Tuesday's intervals, not to add fitness. If your legs feel heavy, go slower. There is no floor on this pace.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed. Just ease into the run from the first step.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 2–3 minutes. This is a great day for a few minutes of gentle foam rolling on the calves and Achilles area if that's part of your routine.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Wednesday is a deliberate recovery day. After Tuesday's interval session, your legs need active flushing rather than rest or another stimulus. Running very easy (5:56/km or slower) increases blood flow to repair muscle tissue without adding meaningful fatigue. This is one of the most important runs of the week — not because it builds fitness, but because it protects your ability to train well on Thursday and Sunday. Your training log shows you've been nailing these recovery runs at 5:56/km, which is exactly right.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Threshold Tempo Run\",\"target_distance_km\":12,\"target_duration_minutes\":53,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":268,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":11,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog. Gradually build from very easy to the lower end of your easy range. Your body should feel warm and loose before the tempo begins.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":268,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"8 km continuous at threshold pace (4:28/km). This is comfortably hard — you could speak a few words but not hold a conversation. Focus on even splits; resist the urge to negative split aggressively.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":11,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog to bring your heart rate down and begin the recovery process.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"2 km easy jog with a gradual build. Optional: 2–3 strides at the end of the warmup to transition your legs into tempo effort.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2 km easy jog, then walk 3–5 minutes. Calf and hip flexor stretching recommended. Pay attention to how your left Achilles feels post-run — any unusual tightness is worth noting.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Thursday's tempo run is the cornerstone quality session of your maintenance week. The 8 km at 4:28/km (threshold pace) targets your lactate threshold — the physiological marker most closely correlated with marathon performance. In a maintenance context, the goal is to hold this fitness, not extend it. Keeping the tempo segment at 8 km (rather than pushing to 10 km) is intentional: it delivers the full threshold stimulus without the recovery cost of a longer effort. This structure mirrors your recent successful tempo sessions exactly.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":322,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Steady easy aerobic effort. Aim for the middle of your easy range (5:30–5:45/km). This is a feel-good run — no structure, no pressure, just consistent aerobic work.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Ease into the first kilometre. No formal warmup needed.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 2–3 minutes after finishing. Light stretching as desired.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Friday's easy run serves as an aerobic top-up between Thursday's tempo and Sunday's long run. Keeping it genuinely easy (not drifting toward marathon pace) is important — you want to arrive at Sunday's long run with fresh legs. Eight kilometres at easy pace adds aerobic volume without meaningful fatigue accumulation. Think of this as maintenance of your aerobic base, not a training stimulus in itself.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"title\":\"Active Recovery Cross-Training\",\"target_distance_km\":0,\"target_duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":0,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":0,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":0,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Low-impact aerobic activity: cycling, swimming, yoga, or light strength work. Heart rate should stay well below your easy running HR — this is restorative, not a training stimulus. If you feel genuinely tired, 20–30 minutes is perfectly sufficient.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No structured warmup needed. Ease into whatever activity you choose.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5 minutes of gentle stretching, particularly calves, hip flexors, and hamstrings. This is a great day for any mobility work you enjoy.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is a deliberate buffer between Friday's easy run and Sunday's long run. Rather than a complete rest day (which can leave legs feeling stiff), light cross-training keeps blood flowing and maintains the movement habit without adding running stress. Cycling or swimming are particularly good options given your Achilles history — they provide aerobic stimulus with zero impact load. If life gets busy and you need to make this a full rest day, that's a completely valid choice. Your long run on Sunday is the priority.\",\"perceived_effort\":2},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":20,\"target_duration_minutes\":119,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":339,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 2 km very easy — slower than your easy pace if needed. Let your body fully wake up before settling into long run rhythm.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":99,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Steady aerobic effort at 5:56/km. The goal is time on feet and aerobic development, not pace. If conditions are warm or you feel fatigued, slowing to 6:10–6:20/km is completely appropriate. Do not let this drift toward marathon pace — that changes the physiological stimulus entirely.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 2 km deliberately slower. Ease off the effort and begin the recovery process before you stop.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start very easy. If you do this run in the morning, give yourself 10–15 minutes of gentle movement before heading out — your Achilles in particular benefits from being properly warmed up before sustained effort.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 5–10 minutes after finishing. Prioritise refuelling within 30–45 minutes. Gentle calf stretching and elevation of the legs if possible. This is the most important recovery window of the week.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Sunday's long run is the centrepiece of your maintenance week. At 20 km, it matches your current long run distance — in a maintenance phase, there's no need to extend it further. The pace target of 5:56/km (your easy ceiling) keeps this firmly in aerobic territory, which is exactly right: long runs derive their value from duration and aerobic stimulus, not pace. Your recent long runs (20–21 km at 5:56/km) have been executed perfectly. One thing worth watching: your Chicago Marathon in October was run in warm conditions and came in slower than your Boston PR. Your fitness is clearly strong — the long run pace you've been using is appropriate and protective, especially given your Achilles history. Stay patient with the pace and trust the process.\",\"perceived_effort\":6}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
